{{Orphan|date=January 2018}}
'''Anthony D. Andre''' is a researcher, practitioner and academic in the fields of [[human factors]], [[ergonomics]], [[usability]] and product design. He is the founding principal of Interface Analysis Associates, a human factors and ergonomics consultancy.<ref>[http://www.packagingdigest.com/pharmaceutical-packaging/study-reveals-shortcomings-drug-vial-warning-labels Packaging Materials, Equipment, and News | Packaging Digest<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He is a founding member and adjunct professor of the HF/E Graduate Program at [[San Jose State University]].<ref>[http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1999-08-23/entertainment/9908230239_1_stress-injuries-ergonomics-repetitive-stress Improper mouse use a plaque in workplace - Baltimore Sun<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324442304578236480316234780 "Phones Are a Big-Screen Hit but a Bit of a Fashion Challenge"]. ''Wall Street Journal'' Shira Ovide, Jan. 15, 2013</ref> He has served as president of the [[Human Factors and Ergonomics Society]]. Andre is a Certified Professional Ergonomist (CPE), recognized by the Board of Certification of Professional Ergonomists (BCPE).<ref>[http://www.news-medical.net/news/20100527/Prohibiting-cap-messages-will-increase-medication-errors-Survey.aspx "Prohibiting cap messages will increase medication errors: Survey"]. ''News Medical'', May 27, 2010.</ref>
==Early life and education== In 1987, Andre received a Bachelor of Science in Experimental and Cognitive Psychology from the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]]. In 1991, he received a Ph.D. in Human Factors and Ergonomics (emphasis in Engineering Psychology), also from University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.
==Career== Andre worked at [[Ames Research Center|NASA Ames Research Center]] in Mountain View, CA, as a Principal Scientist and Senior Design Researcher from 1992 until 1996. He studied interfaces for aircraft cockpits and air traffic management systems.
In 1993, Andre founded Interface Analysis Associates (IAA), a Human Factors, Usability & Ergonomics consulting firm.<ref>[http://bangordailynews.com/2012/07/16/business/pedal-pusher-desk-bike-marketer-hopes-to-get-more-workers-into-shape/ "Pedal pusher: Desk-bike marketer hopes to get more workers into shape"]. ''BDN Maine'', Sue McAllister, San Jose Mercury News, July 16, 2012</ref> This company operated a usability testing lab in the San Francisco Bay Area. Currently located in [[Saratoga, California|Saratoga]], CA, IAA has evaluated, designed, or tested more than 1000 products for over 400 clients in a variety of domains. One of these products was an automatic external defibrillator,<ref name="AlbertTullis2013">{{cite book|author1=William Albert|author2=Thomas Tullis|title=Measuring the User Experience: Collecting, Analyzing, and Presenting Usability Metrics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bPhLeMBLEkAC&pg=PA5|date=23 May 2013|publisher=[[Newnes]]|isbn=978-0-12-415792-7|pages=5–}}</ref> and in 2009, IAA received the User-Centered Design Award, given by HFES’s Product Design Technical Group, for their role in this design. In 2007, IAA’s design of a bio-tech software application was voted the Best New Life Science Product in 2007.
Andre became a professor at [[San Jose State University]]<ref>[http://www.in-pharmatechnologist.com/Drug-Delivery/Proposed-USP-limits-on-vial-labelling-ambiguous-and-vague-says-CAPS Proposed USP limits on vial labelling “ambiguous and vague”, says CAPS<!-- Bot generated title -->]. ''Pharmatechnologist''.</ref><ref>[https://www.wired.com/2008/10/laptop-makers-s/ "Laptop Makers Shy Away From Multitouch Technology"]. ''Wired'', Priya Ganapati October 1, 2008.</ref> in 1993, and co-founded the university’s Human Factors and Ergonomics Graduate Program.<ref>SJSU HF/E, http://www.engr.sjsu.edu/hfe/faculty/faculty-intro</ref> He taught graduate courses over a period of 19 years, including Introduction to Ergonomics, Human Factors Experiments, Usability Evaluation and Testing, Cognitive Engineering, Engineering Psychology and an HF/E Professional Seminar.<ref>[http://www.bendbulletin.com/news/1379286-151/pedal-pusher-desk-bike-marketer-hopes-to-get-more# "Pedal pusher: Desk-bike marketer hopes to get more workers in shape"]. ''Bend Bulletin''.</ref> Andre also serves as a project and thesis advisor, on the graduate program committee and as the advisor of the SJSU Student Chapter of HFES. In 2009, Andre was named Outstanding Lecturer by the Davidson College of Engineering, San Jose State University.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}
Andre joined the [[Human Factors and Ergonomics Society]]<ref>[http://www.sv411.com/index.php/2013/05/ambulant-inc-wingo-case/ "Startup Watch: Ambulant Inc.’s Wingo Case"]. ''SV411'', by Jennifer Elias | May 21, 2013</ref> in 1989, and has held leadership positions, including serving as president in 2010-2011.<ref>[https://www.hfes.org//Web/AboutHFES/leadership.html Human Factors and Ergonomics Society: Leadership<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 2012, he initiated and chaired the 2012 HFES Symposium on Human Factors and Ergonomics in Health Care.
Andre has been frequently interviewed in news reports about high tech product design.<ref>[http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/technology/2008/06/the-fingernail.html "The iPhone fingernail problem"]. ''Los Angeles Times'', June 12, 2008</ref><ref>[http://macdailynews.com/2010/02/08/experts_ipads_could_encourage_bad_posture_introduce_musculoskeletal_issues/ "Experts: iPads could encourage bad posture, introduce musculoskeletal issues"]. ''Mac News Daily'', Monday, February 8, 2010</ref>
